node.text:
With Halloween weekend approaching, we asked some campus representatives to share some valuable advice on how to keep you and your peers safe this spooky season! 👻 The impact of COVID-19 means our Chico State community will have to celebrate Halloween a little differently this year. We encourage Wildcats to rise to the challenge and avoid large gatherings. Instead, be creative with how you celebrate by gathering virtually or with roommates. Butte County has made improving progress in reopening and limiting the spread of COVID-19, and it's critical to do your part so we don't backtrack on the progress our community has already made. 

🚨 If you see something inappropriate or dangerous, speak up and call 911. 🚨 If you notice a large gathering, you can contact University Police through their anonymous tip form. It's important to keep our Wildcat family safe and take care of each other. The greatest thing we can do in this time is continuing to make progress on the pandemic and turning towards a more normal life. Stay safe this Halloween, Wildcats! 🎃 🐾

node.text:
This summer, graduate student He-Lo Ramirez is helping pilot a new @americorps program at Chico State to educate the community on Traditional Ecological Knowledge.

He-Lo spent his summers growing up at the Feather-River Canyon, uncovering wild onions from the soil, fishing for trout from the icy streams and living off the land. Through this new program, He-Lo hopes to inspire a passion in the next generation for eating wild plants and conserving the natural world. "The land itself just needs to be taken care of, and it will take care of you in return.”

Read the full story at Chico State Today: today.csuchico.edu

📸🌲: @jasonhalley_csu
